Wash and dry all produce. Preheat broiler to high or oven to 500 degrees. In a small #pot, combine @veggie stock concentrate{1} and 4 cups @water{4%cups}. Bring to a boil and reduce to a simmer over low heat.

Halve, peel, and @yellow onion{1}(peeled and diced). Mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}(minced). Drain and pat @artichokes{1%jar} dry with a #paper towel{}, then chop into bite-size pieces. Cut @button mushrooms{4%ounce} into quarters. Finely chop @parsley{1/4%ounce}.

In a medium #pot, heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{1%tablespoon} over medium-high heat. Add onion and cook until softened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Add garlic and mushrooms and cook until mushrooms have started to soften, another ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add @Arborio rice{3/4%cup} to pot and stir until grains are translucent, about ~{1%minute}. Add warm stock 1/4 cup at a time, stirring after each addition. Let rice absorb stock before adding more.

While risotto cooks, place artichoke hearts on a #baking sheet{} and toss with a drizzle of olive oil and a pinch of @pepper{}. Broil until crisped and starting to brown, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Once rice is al dente, add broiled artichoke hearts, parsley, and half the @Parmesan cheese{1/4%cup} to risotto. Stir to combine. Season to taste with @salt{} and pepper. Divide risotto between plates and top with @pine nuts{1%ounce} and remaining cheese.

> You could think of risotto as a blank canvas that can be embellished with
> whatever ingredients you please. Here, we're dressing it up with tender
> roasted artichoke hearts, earthy mushrooms, and some pine nuts for crunch.
> Altogether, it makes for a masterful composition that's a delight to take in.